7371901625516133678.voice_to_text: A little over one month later I'm back with an update. I wanted to show you how all my little propagations are doing the ones that I stuck in with a cut up golden pothos that you see right here. So, I did this technique with more than I'd originally posted about in the video. As you can see right here, I did it with this Rosemary. I've Learned at least a few different lessons I'm gonna share with you from this experiment. The first lesson is that there's some plants that this technique works very well with. This Rosemary for instance— she's doing great got lots of little root growth I'll probably let her go for another month or two. It also really worked well with the flaming Katy’s. With it's originally intended plant it did not work well. It’s quite dead and rotted 🥲 Moment of silence for the fallen 🤧 but so um [Lesson #2] as it turns out from Google no matter what I did this one wouldn't have survived because she needed to have some of her  original root mass to come with her. So, yeah originally she started folding in her  leaves and I'm like “No baby your stem is still great keep holding on.” So I Frankenstein the hell out of her with  some tape to hold her open. Just thinking: “You got this take in that light you're gonna you're gonna survive I swear!”  She didn’t 🥲🥲 No— she eventually just continued to rot and I felt like a terrible person.  Clearly I still have much to learn about  being a plant mom. 7368849928795360558.voice_to_text: are you a serial plant killer you know what I used to be too until I Learned this one little trick and it's the skewer method now this is a super simple way to check to see if your plants need water or not a lot of the times your plant will die because it's either under watered or overwatered but the skewer method really will just completely change the game when it comes to caring for plants so let me show you how to check so I have this beautiful plant right here and here's my skewer I'm gonna shove this skewer down into this plant and i'mma pull it back out now let's take a look at this skewer now that I pulled it out now if I look at the skewer I can see that dirt stuck to the very bottom of this skewer but if you look at the top part there's nothing stuck to it which tells me that the top half of that soil on that plant is dry the dirt will stick to the skewer where the plant is wet so with this tells me that it's only like the bottom inch to an inch and a half that is wet on this plant which tells me this plant needs water now we're gonna check this one and see what she looks like cause I just gave her some water the other day so she should be a little more wet but let's pull this skewer out and I'm trying to do this with one hand for y'all so you can see what the heck I'm doing oh so look at that one see all the dirt that stuck to this this plant is really good and wet so all that dirt that stuck to it that's telling me it doesn't need water right now now I check my plants like this about twice a week and it's super simple because the skewer will it's gonna tell you if your plant needs water or not and this is one of the simplest and quickest ways that you can check that way you know whether you need to feed your plant or just let it chill out until the next time you check I hope this helps I love y'all have a good

7366124924617936161.voice_to_text: Random fact that only you know because of your weird, specific job. Let me introduce you to the Victoria water platter, one of the most amazing plants in the world. The Victoria water platters are native to the tropics of South America and related to water lilies. Their leaves grow up to about 4 to 6 feet in diameter. For reference, I'm 6 feet tall here in this picture. One of the coolest things about them is that their flowers actually exhibit thermogenesis. This means that they create their own heat, and they can actually reach temperatures of up to 90 degrees Fahrenheit. We're just getting started. Each flower only blooms for two nights. The first night, the flower is white and female, like you see here. The heat attracts nocturnal beetles, which crawl in through this opening here. The flower provides carbohydrate reserves, which keeps the beetle orgy going all night long. In the morning, the flower closes up, trapping the beetles inside. On the second night, the flower opens as a pink male and begins releasing pollen as a trap. Beetles escape. They move past the anthers, carrying pollen with them to a fresh female flower for round two. They're also covered in insane spine.

7249150404204727594.video_description: Replying to @Sam Bivans   Can you tell the difference? The Philodendron White Knight, Wizard, and Princess are so similar, this has been the easiest way for me to identify them! #plantsoftiktok #plantparent #plantsmakemehappy #houseplants #philodendron #philodendronwhiteknight #philodendronwhiteprincess #philodendronwhitewizard #planthelp
7249150404204727594.voice_to_text: So I've gotten this question a lot of what's the difference between a philodendron white knight, white wizard, and white princess? And I have all 3 of my collection now so I can show you. In terms of care and growth, habit would say that all 3 of these are incredibly similar. And as you can tell by the foliage, they look a lot alike. So if you're trying to go just based off of the leaves, you're probably gonna have a hard time. The secret and telling the difference with these babies is going to be looking at the stems. A philodendron White Princess is going to have green stems with pink variegation along the margin. It is rare, but it can happen that a white Princess pushes out pink variegation instead of white, but it usually is going to fade to white eventually. The White Wizard looks really similar, but the stem is going to be completely green, no signs of pink. And lastly, the philodendron White Knight is going to have a darker red kind of burgundy stem, and that's going to be really apparent, especially on that new growth. Let me know what's your favorite!

7237566882704919850.video_description: I planted this Chamomile last year as a young seedling to accompany my brassicas. One here and one on the opposite raised bed. Perfect companion for basil, cucumbers and brassicas such as kale, cabbage, broccoli, cauliflower, kale, Brussels sprouts, kohlrabi, turnips, radishes. Their aroma deters cabbage pests. That’s what I had growing in these beds last year. This year, I will need to clear the space to make room for gourds (squashes and melons). She attracts a lot of pollinators. I’ve seen lady bugs and bees visit her a lot. The one bunch of seedling actually multiplied to 2 bundles as seen here. I spread her a little so it doesn’t suffocate the Thyme near her. I am calling her Camilla as she is becoming a force in my garden. Looks like she’s is a German Chamomile as supposed to a Roman Chamomile. The German chamomile is about 24”, prolific bloomer, an annual, dies after flowering but set seeds that comes back the following year while a Roman Chamomile is a perennial and shorter in size. I actually saved some seeds last year but learning now that I may not need them. Will save for the flowers for loose tea instead. Chamomile is known as a good herbal tea for calming the stomach and anxiety and promoting sleep. However it may not be good for people with asthma especially with allergies to ragweed or the asteraceae family (ie. aster, daisies, chrysanthemums, etc.) 🤔🤚🏼😳  I’m afraid if I don’t relocate or cut her back soon she will sow her seeds everywhere and will grow all over my beautiful rock bed. I will keep you posted but in the meantime, join me in enjoying her beauty. #garden #chamomile #chamomiletea #germanchamomile #herbal #herb #plants #companionplanting #zone6b

And I'm gonna have to move her because I don't want her spreading too much in here. Otherwise, I'm just gonna cut her back. Can't seem to make myself do that, because. Look how beautiful. Look at that. So much chamomile tea in the future here. So beautiful. Look at her. I think I shall name her Camilla.
